TAKE TWO

### Plot Parameters
The first thing to define is the overall footprint of the building.
What's fairly liberating about this step, and helpful to the generation uniqueness is that there are actually two footprints to consider.
The X and Y of the entire plot, and then the amount of stories (Z).

We can consider this our constant. This can never change (We would have to buy another plot of land to change it). 
So this is the first thing we set, and then all the rest of the generation process has to work within that constraint.

It's liberating in the sense that even if there's only space for a few apartments on a single floor, the building can still pack in more units vertically.
For generation it makes things very interesting as a small narrow space can still be viable for a high end luxury tower, while a large plot can be packed densely with less stories for a lower socio economic residential space.

By using the XY size and shape as a limit therefore makes it a bit easier to reason about certain generated architecture, such as corridor paths, access point placements and how many apartments can actually fit on each floor.

So the first step of the entire process is going to be to define the overall plot size and shape.


