### Apartment Parameters

Now that we have a way to define the overall plot (which later can be derived from a simply divided city block), we now need to define the apartment parameters.

We are essentially jumping right into creating the living space we want to serve and ignoring access and circulation for now.

There are a few variables we could use here which, when combined, form the type of tenants we are designing for.
- Apartment Layout: Is this building serving familiies, students, single professionals, elites? Japan has some good classifications for this. 1R, 1K, 1DK, 1LDK, 2LDK, etc.
- Location: Is this building in the city center, or in the suburbs? Is it in a high density area where space is at a premium, or is it in a more sprawling area where space is abundant?
- Building Age: When was this building built? Older buildings tend to have larger units. Large does not mean more luxurious. So the size of the apartment is not necessarily a direct correlation to the wealth of the tenants.
- Target Demographic: How wealthy are the tenants? This can influence the spacing of the apartments, and the amount of emphasis pput on exterior features such as balconies and windows.

At this stage we are roleplaying as the real estate developer, making sure to create the most efficient and profitable building possible for the target demographic.
We can pack low socio economic tenants more densely, and omit exterior features. However high end luxury apartments need to have more spacing between them so as to consider mitigating sound pollutions and emphasizing the amount of light that can come in.

We can create the general apartment standalone for now and then simply place them primitively in the plot.
We want to create the ideal apartment for the demographic and plot size, and then derive the access and circulation from there.
This way we are serving the living space first, and making compromises on the circulation and access second, rather than the other way around.

Note that at this point we are looking only at the internal layout of the apartment, and not thinking about exterior features such as balconies and windows yet. 
That comes later.

If our intended apartment layout doesnt fit enough in the plot, then we do have the option to build vertical. A 2 story apartment for example.

What is enough? Minimum 4 apartments per floor for a building to be viable.
If we can not fit 4 apartments per floor, then we, as the developer have made a poor investment and must reconsider our demographic for the plot we are working with.

Important to note, apartment blocks tend to serve one layout type. So we are not trying to fit a mix of 1R, 1K, 1DK, 1LDK, 2LDK, etc in the same building. 
We are picking one layout and then packing it as efficiently as possible.

