   height="44rem" /%}

### Exterior Features

Once the apartment blocks exist, the next layer is how those units meet the outside.

This is where the layout starts to feel less like abstract occupancy and more like housing:

- balconies can project from units that have real exterior exposure
- windows can be distributed along exposed walls
- balcony rails can be treated separately from full-height walls

That also means this stage has to be a little more selective. Not every apartment should automatically receive the same exterior treatment.

For example:

- enclosed layouts should not suddenly grow exterior balconies into the courtyard void
- a wall that already opens onto a balcony does not also need a window pass layered on top of it
- and inner apartments only work if there is still enough true remaining space for them after circulation and access are carved out

So stage four is really about adding facade logic on top of the placement pass:

- keep the apartment placement from stage three
- detect which apartment edges are genuinely exterior-facing
- add windows where that makes sense
- add balconies only where they have a believable outside condition

It is still not interior design yet. It is the first point where the apartment blocks begin to read like actual homes with an outside face.

